Name: WCM/BNY Mellon Focused Growth ADR ETF
Description: large-cap growth portfolio for the non-U.S. universe. The portfolio is purposely very different from international benchmarks and other international funds. AADR achieves this differentiation by concentration (20–30 holdings) and a focus on traditional growth sectors such as technology, healthcare and consumer staples/discretionary. Developed Europe 55%

Name: MSCI All Country Asia ex Jpn Idx
SPDR MSCI ACWI IMI
Description: The index is a free float-adjusted market capitalization-weighted index that is designed to measure the combined equity market performance of developed and emerging markets. The index covers approximately 98% of the global equity investment opportunity set

Name: MSCI All Country World Minimum Volatility Index Fund
Description: The index aims to re?ect the performance characteristics of a minimum variance strategy applied to large and mid cap equities across 45 Developed and Emerging Markets countries . The index is calculated by optimizing the MSCI ACWI Index, its parent index, for the lowest absolute risk (within a given set of constraints). Historically, the index has shown lower beta and volatility characteristics relative to the MSCI ACWI Index

Name: Market Vectors Africa Index ETF
Description: This ETF offers exposure to publicly traded companies that are headquartered in Africa or that generate the majority of their revenues within the continent. This ETF tracks the Dow Jones Africa Titans 50 Index. This ETF is relatively well balanced, including much more than just South Africa; Nigeria, Egypt, and Morocco are some of the other allocations made in this portfolio. Investors who wish to achieve country-specific exposure should consider the MSCI South Africa Index Fund (EZA).

Name: Core Total US Bond Market ETF
Description: One of the most popular fixed income funds, AGG offers exposure to U.S. investment grade debt. This fund tracks the Barclays Capital U.S. Aggregate Bond Index. With over 1,000 holdings in total, AGG gives investors deep, broad-based, exposure and its fairly cheap expense ratio makes it quite the attractive core holding for many long-term investment portfolios. AGG’s underlying holdings are mainly U.S. Treasuries and Mortgage Backed Securities, although corporate bonds also receive a decent allocation. Less than 10% of the funds holdings are rated “BBB” or lower, and exposure in terms of time to maturity is fairly well balanced although there is more of a focus on longer-term debt. Investors who would prefer to increase their U.S. corporate bond exposure ought to consider LQD or CBND instead.  Cost conscious investors should also note that AGG is available for commission free trading on Fidelty, and TD Ameritrade.:::.

Name: Accuvest Global Long Short ETF
Description: proprietary country ranking model (40 factors). Highly-ranked countries - long; least-ranked - short. ETF of single-country ETFs. Long position 30% in EM, short position 45% in EM.

Name: S&P Asia 50 Index
Description: 50 leading companies from four Asian countries: Hong Kong, South Korea, Singapore, and Taiwan.

Name: WisdomTree Asia Local Debt ETF
Description: This ETF invests in local currency debt from issuers in South Korea, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Hong Kong, China, India, Thailand, Philippines, Taiwan, and the developed markets of Australia and New Zealand. ALD is one of a kind not only because the fund is actively managed, but also because it’s the first ETF to focus exclusively on Asian debt. The fund will also implement a tiered investment approach, with markets deemed to maintain larger and more liquid debt receiving higher weightings in the fund. A single country cap of 20% will be applied. ALD’s holdings are primarily of high quality and rated “A” or higher, while a small percentage are ranked BBB and lower. In terms of duration there is a major bias towards shorter-term securities, as over two-thirds of the underlying holdings have maturities of 5 years or less.:::.

Name: AlphaClone Alternative Alpha ETF
Description:
ETF of hedge funds holdings: tracks the performance of US-traded equity securities to which hedge funds and institutional investors have disclosed significant exposure. Then ranks hedge funds and institutional investors based on the efficacy of replicating their publicity disclosed positions. Equities are selected from those managers with the highest ranking, or "Clone Score". The index can vary between being long only and market hedged (50% short exposure to the S&P 500 index). The hedge is triggered on or off when the S&P 500 crosses its 200 day moving 
average at any month end.

Name: JPMorgan Alerian MLP Index ETN
Description: Alerian MLP Index is a market-cap weighted, float-adjusted index created to provide a comprehensive benchmark for investors to track the performance of the energy MLP sector. The majority of MLPs currently operate in the energy infrastructure industry, owning assets such as pipelines that transport crude oil, natural gas and other refined petroleum products. Master limited partnerships (MLPs). Given that so many MLPs are built around midstream, storage or energy transportation businesses, it’s not too surprising that the energy markets have a meaningful influence on these units. While some MLPs operate in regulated environments where prices are carefully controlled, others do not – in either case, changes in volume (often tied to the economic conditions of the region or country) can significantly impact anticipated distributions and unit prices. MLP ETFs/ETNs are best suited for those more interested in steady income accumulation as opposed to capital gains. Although MLPs don’t tend to be volatile on a day-to-day basis, they can move quite dramatically in response to new interest rate expectations or proposed changes to tax laws.

Name: ALPS Alerian MLP ETF
Description: Provide the exposure to 25 US energy infrastructure Master Limited Partnerships that earn the majority of their cash flow from the transportation, storage, and processing of energy commodities. The Fund’s accrued deferred tax liability, if any, is reflected each day in the Fund’s net asset value per share. The deferred income tax expense/(benefit) represents an estimate of the Fund’s potential tax expense/(benefit) if it were to recognize the unrealized gains/(losses) in the portfolio

Name: UBS E-TRACS Alerian MLP Index ETN
Description: Master limited partnerships (MLPs). Given that so many MLPs are built around midstream, storage or energy transportation businesses, it’s not too surprising that the energy markets have a meaningful influence on these units. While some MLPs operate in regulated environments where prices are carefully controlled, others do not – in either case, changes in volume (often tied to the economic conditions of the region or country) can significantly impact anticipated distributions and unit prices. MLP ETFs/ETNs are best suited for those more interested in steady income accumulation as opposed to capital gains. Although MLPs don’t tend to be volatile on a day-to-day basis, they can move quite dramatically in response to new interest rate expectations or proposed changes to tax laws.

Name: FTSE Andean 40 ETF
Description: 40 largest companies in Chile, Colombia, and Peru.

Name: Market Vectors Fallen Angel HY Bond ETF
Description: This ETF offers exposure to below investment grade corporate bonds denominated in U.S. dollars, issued in the U.S. domestic market, and that were rated investment grade at the time of issuance. The bonds of these companies were once categorized as having relativity low risk, but have since been downgraded to “junk” status. ANGL provides investors with an intriguing opportunity: downgrades lead to significant declines in price, which can create an opportunity to purchase these securities at a discount to their intrinsic value. Taking a closer look under the hood of ANGL reveals that the underlying bonds are typically from large, established companies that fall into the higher end of the junk bond credit quality spectrum.::.

Name: Global X FTSE Argentina 20 ETF
Description: This ETF focuses on companies who generate a substantial amount of their revenues in Argentina. From a sector standpoint, ARGT focuses on basic materials and financial services. This country is currently saddled with severe inflation and political tensions that make it the riskiest holding of this particular portfolio. ARGT features 22 holdings that focus on the basic materials and financial sectors of the Argentinian economy. One interesting thing to note is that the product makes allocations to companies of a market capitalization sizes, giving it diversity in that aspect. Like Colombia, until this economy falls under more stability, it shouldn’t represent a major chunk of any portfolio.:::.

Name: Global X FTSE ASEAN 40 ETF
Description: 40 largest companies in the five ASEAN regions: Indonesia, Philippines, Singapore (40%), Malaysia (30%) and Thailand. Financials - 40%

Name: WisdomTree Australia & NZ Debt
Description: This ETF invests in Australian and New Zealand debt securities denominated in the local currency. The fund invests in government, semi-government, and supranational bonds that have credit rating of AA or above. Australian and New Zealand debt securities tend to have relatively higher yields when compared to other developed market bonds. AUNZ’s strucutre allows investors to gain exposure to both debt and currency movements in Australia and New Zealand. Both countires are major exporters of commodities, which has contributed to their economy’s tremendous growth and strength. AUNZ offers investors an opportunity to profit from the appreciation of Australia’s and New Zealand’s currencies as the demand for raw materials, industrial goods, and agricultural products continues to grow.:::.

Name: iPath GEMS Asia 8 ETN
Description: Total return on local currencies in specified Asian markets through short-term, liquid and diversified instruments. The Index constituent currencies are the Indonesian rupiah, the Indian rupee, the Philippine peso, the South Korean won, the Thai baht, the Malaysian ringgit, the Taiwanese dollar and the Chinese yuan.

Name: SPDR Nuveen Barclays Cap Build Amer Bd
iPath DJ-UBS Cotton TR Sub-Idx ETN
iPath Pure Beta Broad Commodity ETN
E-TRACS 2xLeveraged Long Wells Fargo Business Development Company ETN
Description: The index is a float adjusted, capitalization-weighted Index that is intended to measure the performance of all Business Development Companies that are listed on the New York Stock Exchange or NASDAQ and satisfy specified market capitalization and other eligibility requirements. To qualify as a BDC, the company must be registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission and have elected to be regulated as a BDC under the Investment Company Act of 1940

Name: UBS E-TRACS Wells Fargo Bus Dev Comp ETN
Description: This ETF offers exposure to the performance of all Business Development Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange or NASDAQ. This ETF tracks the Wells Fargo Business Development Company Index. This ETF is one of a kind in that it offers targeted exposure within a selective corner of the small cap equity market that bears a risk profile similar to venture capital investments–an asset class that would otherwise be difficult for most investors to access. Business Development Companies help grow small businesses in the initial stages of their development, however unlike venture capital funds, BDCs allow smaller, non-accredited investors to invest in startup companies.It should be noted that BDCS is an ETN, meaning that investors are exposed to the credit risk of the issuing institution. Those who would prefer to avoid the ETN structure may want to examine PDP, an ETF from PowerShares that offers exposure to global private equity companies. BDCS’s hefty expense fee of 0.85%.:::.

Name: PowerShares DB Base Metals Dble Long ETN
Barron's 400SM ETF
Description: Invests in the highest rated companies in the U.S. stock market according to MarketGrader's fundamental analysis, which measures them based on growth, valuation, profitability and cash flow. All 400 components in the underlying index are equally weighted at each semi-annual rebalance. Consum Discr 22%, IT 17%

Name: ProShares Ultra Nasdaq Biotechnology
Description: The NASDAQ Biotechnology Index is a modified capitalization weighted index that includes securities of The NASDAQ Stock Market listed companies that are classified as either biotechnology or pharmaceutical. This Ultra ProShares ETF seeks a return that is 2x the return of an index or other benchmark.

Name: First Trust BICK Index
Description: largest and most liquid public companies that are domiciled in Brazil, India, Mainland China and South Korea

Name: ProShares UltraShort Nasdaq Biotech
Description: The NASDAQ Biotechnology Index is a modified capitalization weighted index that includes securities of The NASDAQ Stock Market listed companies that are classified as either biotechnology or pharmaceutical. This Ultra ProShares ETF seeks a return that is -2x the return of an index or other benchmark.

Name: Market Vectors Gaming ETF
Description: This fund provides exposure to the global gaming industry. This ETF is made up of around fifty holdings that generate the majority of their revenues in the global gaming industry. U.S. companies makes up about a third of the total assets, with the rest going to f Hong Kong, Malaysia, the U.K. and Australia. Nine of the top ten holdings are in resort casinos, which account for approximately half of the portfolio from an industry breakdown perspective.:::.

Name: iPath Pure Beta Precious Metals ETN
Vanguard Total Bond Market ETF
Description: This ETF offers exposure to investment grade sector of the U.S. corporate bond market, including corporate bonds, Treasuries, and debt issued by agencies of the U.S. government. U.S. Treasuries receive the heaviest allocation, while exposure is also diversified across U.S. Corporate and Agency bonds. We like BND over AGG because of the advantages in expense ratio and depth of holdings.:::.

Name: PowerShares DB Base Metals Dble Shrt ETN
PowerShares DB Base Metals Short ETN
Global X Brazil Mid Cap ETF
Market Vectors Brazil Small-Cap ETF
Description: This ETF offers exposure to small cap companies that are domiciled and primarily listed on an exchange in Brazil or that generate at least 50% of their revenues in Brazil. BRF is an essential tactical holding since Brazil is a major exporter of everything from sugar and orange juice to soybeans and oil. This ETF holds a basket of approximately 70 securities and is well diversified across mid, small, and micro caps. From a sector breakdown perspective, consumer cyclicals are the top allocation; this is a major benefit in our opinion as BRF’s underlying holdings are well positioned to profit from Brazil’s increasing population growth and favorable local consumption patterns.:::.

Name: EGShares Brazil Infrastructure
Description: ER=0.85% The Indxx Brazil Infrastructure Index is a free-float market capitalization weighted stock market index comprised of 30 leading companies that Indxx, LLC determines to be representative of Brazil's Infrastructure industries, as defined by the Industry Classification Benchmark (ICB).

Name: BulletShares 2015 High Yield Corporate Bond ETF
BulletShares 2016 High Yield Corporate Bond ETF
BulletShares 2017 High Yield Corporate Bond ETF
BulletShares 2018 High Yield Corporate Bond ETF
QuantShares US Market Neut Anti-Beta ETF
Description: equal weighted, dollar neutral and sector neutral. The index rebalances monthly by identifying the lowest beta stocks as long positions and highest beta stocks as short positions, of approximately equal dollar amounts, within each sector

Name: iPath CBOE S&P 500 BuyWrite Index ETN
Description: total rate of return of a hypothetical "buy-write", or "covered call", strategy on the S&P 500 Index. This strategy consists of a hypothetical portfolio consisting of a "long" position indexed to the S&P 500 Index (i.e. purchasing the common stocks included in the S&P 500 Index) and the sale of a succession of one-month, at- or slightly out-of-the-money S&P 500 Index call options that are listed on the Chicago Board Options Exchange.

Name: SPDR Barclays Capital Intl Treasury Bond
Description: BWX tracks the Barclays Capital Global Treasury Ex-US Capped index, a benchmark that invests in local currency-denominated bonds issued by investment-grade countries outside the United States. The fund’s underlying portfolio includes 300 government bonds, of which more than three quarters hold a credit rating of AA or higher.:::.

Name: SPDR Barclays Cap S/T Intl Treasury Bond
WisdomTree Dreyfus Brazilian Real
Description: This ETF offers exposure to the Brazilian Real relative to the U.S. dollar. BZF’s investment objective to achieve total returns reflective of both money market rates in Brazil available to foreign investors and changes in the value of the Brazilian Real relative to the U.S. dollar. Similar to CYB, the fund utilizes currency forwards to accomplish its objective and collateralizes the investment with short-term T-bills. Investors can use this ETF as a tool to hedge exchange rate exposure or bet against the American dollar.:::.

Name: First Trust NASDAQ Global Auto Index
Description: ETF provides targeted exposure to the global auto industry. Only the largest and most liquid companies engaged in the manufacturing of automobiles are represented in this ETF. CARZ features a top-heavy portfolio, with its top ten holdings accounting for about two-thirds of total assets.:::.

Name: SPDR Barclays Cap Issuer Scd Corp Bond
Description: This ETF tracks the Barclays Capital Issuer Scored Corporate Index, which measures the performance of the U.S. corporate bond market and utilizes a fundamental weighting methodology. Most bond ETFs are linked to market cap-weighted indexes, a flawed strategy that ends up giving the largest allocations to the the biggest issuers of debt. CBND’s underlying index uses three fundamental factors to determine the weight given to each issuer among those in the eligible universe: Return on Assets, Interest Coverage, and Current Ratio. CBND has over 3,500 holdings, and in terms of sector allocation, the fund currently allocates only 10% in financial services. LQD is a popular tool for accessing corporate debt, but we believe the methodology used by the underlying index makes CBND a better tool for the long run.::.

Name: WisdomTree Dreyfus Commodity Currency
Description: One feature of CCX that we like is that the fund’s exposure is nicely split between developed and emerging markets. Holdings include: the Brazilian real, Chilean peso, Russian ruble, South African rand, Australian dollar, Canadian dollar, Norwegian Krone, and the New Zealand dollar. CCX is perhaps best classified as an ultra-short term fixed income product since it provides investors with access to international markets that offer juicy short-term yields, compared to the ultra-low money market rates offered in the United States. Historically, currencies of commodity-producing currencies have exhibited increased sensitivity to global growth levels; during economic booms demand for raw material surges, sending both the prices of the commodities and value of related currencies higher. But these currencies have also held up relatively well during periods of slumping commodity prices.::.

Name: WisdomTree Commodity Country Equity
Description: The WisdomTree Commodity Country Equity Index is a fundamentally weighted index that measures the performance of dividend-paying companies from commodity countries selected from the WisdomTree Global Dividend Index. The index is comprised of dividend-paying companies ranked by market capitalization from each of the following commodity countries: Australia, Brazil, Canada, Chile, New Zealand, Norway, Russia and South Africa. Each country has an allocation of approximately 12.5% within the index and up to 20 qualifying companies may be included in each country allocation. Companies are weighted within each country allocation based on annual cash dividends paid

Name: WisdomTree Dreyfus Emerging Currency
Description: This ETF seeks to achieve returns that reflect both money market rates in certain emerging market countries and changes in the value of these currencies relative to the U.S. dollar. CEW is backed by an investment team that screens and selects a basket of up to 12 emerging market currencies. Most of CEW’s holdings are in the form of government bonds or repurchase agreements. While interest rates in the U.S. are near zero (and are expected to remain at record low levels for some time), money market accounts in many emerging market economies offer material yields. The fund offers investors exposure to rapidly appreciating currencies which have grown more in demand as emerging markets make up a bigger piece of world trade. Currently, the fund is heavily weighted in exposure to Brazil, South Korea, and South Africa offering investors diversified exposure to all emerging geographic regions.:::.

Name: QuantShares US Market Neutral Value ETF
Description: equal weighted, dollar neutral and sector neutral. The index rebalances monthly by identifying the most undervalued stocks as long positions and the most overvalued stocks as short positions, of approximately equal dollar amounts, within each sector.

Name: Global X China Consumer ETF
Description: This index is designed to reflect the performance of the consumer sector in China. It is comprised of selected companies which have their main business operations in the consumer sector and are domiciled in China or have their main business operations in this country.

Name: IQ Canada Small Cap ETF
Description: This ETF provides exposure to the performance of the small cap sector of the Canadian equity market. Canada is home to some of the most abundant gold mines in the world, and maintains massive oil reserves as well. We have opted for small cap exposure because it is more of a “pure play” on the local economy since smaller companies are more sensitive to changes in consumptions patterns and demographic trends.CNDA has about 100 holdings and is very well-balanced, seeing as how no individual security account for more than 3% of total assets. Close to half of all assets are allocated to the basic materials sector, while energy holdings make up the next biggest chunk. Investors should also note that this small cap ETF is actually most heavily invested in mid caps, although small caps do account for about one third of the entire portfolio.:::.

Name: PIMCO Investment Grade Corp Bd Index ETF
iPath DJ-UBS Livestock TR Sub-Idx ETN
Description: COW is a great complement to JJA, in that it is also exclusively invested in agricultural futures contracts, but instead focuses on live cattle and lean hogs. Given the global nature of commodity markets, these futures-based holdings are essential in allowing investors to tap into international price trends for everyday goods.:::.

Name: IQ Real Return ETF
Description: Similar to RRF, CPI is also designed to help investors combat inflation through the use of short-term debt securities. CPI tracks the performance of the IQ CPI Inflation Hedged Index, a rules-based benchmark that utilizes the monthly change in the Consumer Price Index. To achieve its anti-inflation goal, the fund invests primarily in short-term bonds but also has allocations in a variety of asset classes, including domestic and international equities, currencies, commodities, and real estate. With an expense ratio of only 48 basis points, CPI is a cost-effective option for investors seeking to protect themselves against inflation as well as potentially benefit from excess real returns.:::.

Name: Guggenheim China Technology
Description: The Index is designed to measure and monitor the performance of the universe of publicly-traded companies which are based in mainland China, Hong Kong or Macau, are in the Information Technology Sector, as defined by Standard & Poor’s GICS and are open to foreign investment.

Name: Jefferies TR/J CRB Global Commodity Eq
Description: The Jefferies | TR/J CRB Global Commodity Equity Index measures the performance of equity securities of a global universe of listed companies engaged in the production and distribution of commodities and commodity-related products and services in the agriculture, base/industrial metals, energy and precious metals sectors. Agro + Energy = 80%. North America 60%
Short_Name: Jefferies TR/J CRB Global Commodity Eq

Name: IQ Global Agribusiness Small Cap ETF
Description: This ETF will only invest in global small cap companies that are engaged in agribusiness. It is also one of the few funds to offer no exposure to giant market cap companies, instead focusing on riskier medium and small companies in both developing and emerging markets. Japan and the U.S. together have the majority of the holdings with about a quarter of the funds each, but there is also exposure to the China and the Netherlands, including some minority holdings in Ireland. We believe that agricultural commodity producers are well positioned to benefit as the global economic recovery picks up, given the favorable demographic trends fueling population growth and demand for food in growing countries across Latin America and Asia.:::.

Name: Guggenheim Spin-Off
Description: The Index is comprised of approximately 40 securities selected, based on investment and other criteria, from a broad universe of U.S.-traded stocks, American depositary receipts and master limited partnerships. The universe of companies eligible for inclusion in the Index includes companies that have been spun-off within the past two years (but not more recently than six months prior to the applicable rebalancing date), without limitations on market capitalization (including micro-cap securities), but which are primarily small- and mid-cap companies with capitalizations under $10.0 billion.

Name: Credit Suisse Long/Short Liquid Idx ETN
Description: long-short hedge fund strategy without the weighty costs. CSLS is the cheapest offering from the Hedge Fund.

Name: ProShares Credit Suisse 130/30
Description: This ETF tracks an index that employs a 130/30 investment strategy in an attempt to generate alpha. Implementing this strategy includes taking a 100% long position in a benchmark (in this case the S&P 500), short selling 30% of the portfolio, and investing the proceeds in additional long positions. CSM offers a risk and return profile that is very similar to ETFs tracking the S&P 500, including SPY and IVV, but uses a 130/30 strategy in an attempt to outperform traditional market capitalization-weighted benchmarks. The trading history for CSM is relatively short (it was introduced in July 2009), but since its inception it has outperformed the S&P 500 by a material margin, delivering excess returns for investors looking for an alternative way to gain large cap exposure.:::.

Name: Credit Suisse Merger Arbi Liquid Idx ETN
Description: hedge fund investing with merger arbitrage. This strategy involves buying stocks that have been announced as takeover targets but for which the transaction has not yet closed. By investing in these takeover targets, CSMA gains if the transaction is ultimately completed, profiting from the difference between the purchase price and the deal price. Like CSLS, CSMA is an exchange-traded note, which exposes investors to the potential credit risk of the issuing institution.:::.

Name: First Trust ISE Global Copper Index
C-Tracks Citi Volatility Index TR ETN
Description: Directional exposure to the implied volatility of large-cap U.S. stocks. combines a daily rolling long exposure to the third- and fourth-month futures contracts on the CBOE Volatility Index (the “VIX Index”) with a short exposure to the S&P 500 Total Return Index. The VIX futures contracts exposure is constantly maintained, but the weighting of the S&P 500 Total Return Index is variable and determined monthly via a backward-looking linear regression. The level of the VIX Index has historically reverted to a long-term mean level; any increase in the spot level of the VIX Index likely will not continue over time.

Name: Guggenheim Multi-Asset Income
Description: The Index is designed to identify companies with potentially high income and superior risk-return profiles as determined by Zacks Investment Research, Inc., the Fund's index provider. The objective of the Index is to select a diversified group of securities with the potential to have a yield in excess of and outperform, on a risk adjusted basis, the Dow Jones U.S. Select Dividend Index and other benchmark indices. The Index is comprised of approximately 125 to 150 securities.

Name: SPDR Barclays Capital Convertible Bond ETF
SPDR Nuveen Barclays Capital CA Muni Bd
WisdomTree Dreyfus Chinese Yuan
Description: This ETF seeks to achieve total returns reflective of both money market rates in China available to foreign investors and changes in value of the Chinese Yuan relative to the U.S. dollar. CYB focuses on yuan forwards to accomplish its objective and collateralizes the investment with short-term Treasury bills in order to help boost the yield of the product.:::.

Name: PowerShares DB Agriculture Dble Long ETN
DBX MSCI Brazil Hedged Equity ETF
Description: Brazilian equity markets, while at the same time mitigating exposure to fluctuations between the value of the U.S. dollar and Brazilian real

Name: PowerShares DB Commodity Index Tracking
Description: diversified investments in six major commodity classes (including further allocations to gold). With investments in aluminum, corn, gold, heating oil, light crude, and wheat, DBC provides exposure to the most widely-traded commodities in the world. These assets tend to appreciate significantly in tough economic environments as investors cash out of equities and seek out effective stores of value. This ETP is one of the largest and most popular options for investors looking to achieve broad-based commodity exposure. DBC has the potential to add valuable return enhancement and diversification benefits to traditional stock-and-bond portfolios.

Name: DBX MSCI EAFE Hedged Equity ETF
Description: developed equity markets outside of the U.S., while simultaneously hedging out the currency exposure that an investment in international equities entails. Like most EAFE ETFs, DBEF establishes long positions in international stocks, but it also uses short term forward contracts to neutralize the impact of exchange rate fluctuations, essentially isolating the performance of the developed market stocks as the driver of returns. For investors who expect the greenback to strengthen relative to its developed market rivals, DBEF is an appealing option since it establishes a favorable position in the EAFA equities market and should outperform other EAFE ETFs if the U.S. currency appreciates.:::.

Name: DBX MSCI Emerging Mkts Hdgd Equity ETF
Description: Similar to DBEF, this fund offers U.S. dollar-hedged exposure to international equities, but does so with a focus on the lucrative and high growth potential corner of the emerging equities market. DBEM uses short term forward contracts to strip out any exchange rate-related movements, which can have a significant impact on bottom line returns. Given the relatively unstable nature of emerging market currencies, DBEM helps to smooth out overall volatility since the dollar tends to strengthen as market turbulence peaks.The fund maintains a relatively well-balanced, diversified, and deep portfolio, consisting of over 800 securities.:::.

Name: Pring Turner Business Cycle ETF
Description: Conservative strategy. Pring Turner’s “Six-Stage” business cycle strategy. Multi-asset class fund that dynamically allocates among stocks, bonds, inflation-sensitive securities, and cash. Pro-active asset allocation and sector rotation process designed around the stage changes in the business cycle. Equities 60% (incl. 40% US)

Name: DBX MSCI Japan Hedged Equity ETF
PowerShares DB Precious Metals
Description: ETF gives investors futures-based exposure to the price of gold and silver. This fund can be best described as a gold ETF with a slice of silver. While silver prices do tend to be more volatile than those of its yellow counterpart, this precious metal also has the ability to take on safe haven appeal during chaotic times in the market. Additionally, silver demand is largely industrial, which provides for a source of uncorrelated returns that may reduce overall portfolio volatility and enhance bottom-line returns. The taxation of DBP may be somewhat unique, as this fund will incur gains or losses annually regardless of whether or not a position is liquidated. One potentially interesting alternative is GLTR; that product is physically-backed, meaning that the nuances associated with futures-based strategies are eliminated.:::.

Name: PowerShares DB Commodity Dble Short ETN
Guggenheim Defensive Equity
Description: DEF is designed to invest in companies with a history of outperformance during bear markets by identifying firms with conservative accounting practices, stable dividends, and low relative valuations. DEF’s highest sector allocations are to utilities and consumer staples companies, with relatively little weight given to the consumer discretionary and technology industries. DEF’s P/E ratio of approximately 12 indicates a tilt towards value stocks.:::.

Name: WisdomTree Emerging Markets Equity Inc
Description: This ETF offers exposure to the highest dividend yielding stocks from within the WisdomTree Emerging Markets Dividend Index. This ETF offers a way for investors to establish exposure to emerging markets while still concentrating on equities that will pay the highest dividend yields. The underlying index consists of the highest dividend yielding stocks listed in the developing markets of the world, and individual security weightings are determined based on cash dividends paid. Think of DEM as an alternative to popular emerging markets ETFs such as EEM or VWO; the country exposure is relatively similar, and there will be a fair amount of overlap between the individual holdings as well.:::.

Name: WisdomTree SmallCap Dividend
Description: This fund offers exposure to dividend paying equities of smaller companies, which generally offer greater return characteristics but can be significantly more volatile than larger equities. This fund focuses on small cap stocks. Again, the underlying index is fundamentally-weighted, measuring the performance of dividend-paying small cap equities. Think of DES as an alternative to the S&P SmallCap 600 or Russell 2000 that will generally maintain a more material dividend yield from the small cap universe.:::.

Name: PowerShares DB Gold Double Long ETN
WisdomTree Emerging Mkts SmallCap Div
Description: The WisdomTree Emerging Markets SmallCap Dividend Index is a fundamentally weighted index that measures the performance of primarily small cap stocks selected from the WisdomTree Emerging Markets Dividend Index. Companies included in the Index fall within the bottom 10% of total market capitalization of the WisdomTree Emerging Markets Dividend Index as of the annual index measurement date

Name: SPDR Global Dow ETF
Description: The index is a 150-stock index of leading blue chip companies from around the world. The Index includes companies with a long history of success and a wide following among investors that are selected by an Averages Committee comprised of the managing editor of The Wall Street Journal, the head of Dow Jones Indexes research and the head of CME Group Research. The Index is equal-weighted and includes companies from developed and emerging economies as well as those from emerging economic sectors.

Name: WisdomTree Equity Income
Description: The WisdomTree Equity Income Index is a fundamentally weighted index that measures the performance of companies with high dividend yields selected from the WisdomTree Dividend Index. At the index measurement date, companies within the WisdomTree Dividend Index with market capitalizations of at least $200 million and average daily trading volumes of at least $200,000 for the prior three months are ranked by dividend yield.

Name: Athena High Dividend ETF
Description: Managed by AthenaInvest Advisors LLC. US and foreign common stock of issuers of any capitalization range and ADRs. Behavioral Portfolio Management methodology: applying a quantitative ranking of the global universe of securities which are held by the most strategy consistent active equity mutual funds in the highest conviction positions in their portfolios => narrows this universe by a high dividend yield criteria and selects positions for the portfolio based on the highest combined ranking of the two dimensions.

Name: UBS E-TRACS DJ-UBS Commodity Idx TR ETN

Description: Master limited partnerships (MLPs). Given that so many MLPs are built around midstream, storage or energy transportation businesses, it’s not too surprising that the energy markets have a meaningful influence on these units. While some MLPs operate in regulated environments where prices are carefully controlled, others do not – in either case, changes in volume (often tied to the economic conditions of the region or country) can significantly impact anticipated distributions and unit prices. MLP ETFs/ETNs are best suited for those more interested in steady income accumulation as opposed to capital gains. Although MLPs don’t tend to be volatile on a day-to-day basis, they can move quite dramatically in response to new interest rate expectations or proposed changes to tax laws.

The EUR/USD exchange rate is expressed as a rate that reflects the number of U.S. dollars that can be exchanged for one euro in the interbank market for settlement in two days.

Name: MSCI Canada Index
Description: This ETF tracks the MSCI Canada Index, which measures the performance of the broad Canadian equity market. Exposure is tilted towards the energy sector, given Canada’s bountiful oil reserves, as well as the financial services industry. Market-cap bias is also prevalent with this fund as the majority of holdings are giant and large-cap companies, with zero exposure to small or micro-caps. Top holdings include, Royal Bank of Canada, Suncor Energy, Potash Corporation of Saskatchewan, Bank of Montreal, and Barrick Gold Corporation. Investors who want more of a “pure-play” exposure to the Canadian equity market should consider the IQ Canada Small Cap ETF (CNDA).:::.

Name: MSCI Sweden Index
Description: This fund provides investors with access to the Swedish stock market. Sweden is home to a flourishing business environment and is well known for its high standard of living and financial stability amongst developed nations. Sweden has also not strayed from its currency, the krona, since its inception in 1873. This Scandinavian nation is well-positioned to benefit from an improving economic recovery, while still maintaining a more favorable risk/return profile than other countries in the debt-stricken Euro zone. EWD holds a fairly shallow portfolio of 35 stocks, and the top ten holdings account for close to two thirds of total assets. From a sector breakdown perspective, industrial (30%) and financial service (24%) companies receive the greatest allocations. Consumer cyclical, and technology firms also receive adequate allocations, while energy, real estate, and health care holdings are almost entirely overlooked.:::.

Name: Guggenheim MSCI Emerging Markets Eq Wt
Description: This ETF is designed to offer equal weighted exposure to emerging market equities. This ETF includes the same components as the popular MSCI Emerging Markets Index, the benchmark to which VWO and EEM are linked (EWEM, of course, uses an equal-weight approach that gives an equal weighting to every component). EWEM has around 600 holdings diversified across a multitude of sectors, while the majority of the funds holdings are either large or mid-cap sized companies. One drawback of EWEM is that the fund is not very well diversified from a regional perspective, since allocations to Taiwan, South Korea, and China together make up more than 50% of total holdings.:::.

Name: MSCI Switzerland Index
Description: This ETF tracks the performance of the Swiss equity market. EWL holds around 40 Swiss equities, with the top three sector allocations being health care, consumer defensive, and financial services. Top individual allocations go towards food giant Nestle and two massive pharma companies; Novartis and Roche. One potential setback is that EWL invests almost exclusively in giant and large cap firms, with close to three-quarters of total assets going to the top ten holdings alone.:::.

Name: MSCI Malaysia Index
Description: This ETF tracks an index that seeks to offer exposure to the performance of the Malaysian equity market. This ETF consists of about 45 securities, predominantly from giant and large market-cap size companies. EWM allocates close to a third of its total assets to the growing financials services industry overseas, with the second biggest allocation going to industrial companies. Exposure to consumer goods, both cyclical and defensive, as well as communication services is also included.:::.

Name: MSCI Netherlands Invstbl Mkt Idx
Description: This product tracks the MSCI Netherlands Investable Market Index, offering direct exposure to this European country. The Netherlands are in a fairly “safe spot” when considering the dismal scenario that many Eurozone member nations are facing. This ETF gives investors access to the Dutch equity market and holds about 60 securities. Its portfolio however is top-heavy, seeing as how nearly three-quarters of total assets are allocated to the top ten holdings alone.:::.

Name: Guggenheim Russell 1000 Equal Weight
Description: This ETF includes the components of the Russell 1000 Index, which measures the performance of the large-cap U.S. equity market. Because this fund employs an equal-weight strategy, mid-cap size companies account for two-thirds of this funds holdings, while large-cap stocks make up the next biggest chunk. IWB tracks the same index as EWRI, however, it only holds 20% in mid-cap size companies, while the majority are large-cap stocks given the funds traditional cap-weighted methodology. EWRI is fairly diversified across all sectors, with communication services and real estate receiving the smallest allocations at just under 5% a piece. Employing an equal-weight strategy is no easy task and it requires regular re-balancing, which translates into higher expense fees for EWRI when compared to similar funds using a basic cap-weighted methodology.:::.

Name: Guggenheim Russell 2000 Equal Weight
Description: This fund gives investors broad-based exposure to the small-cap U.S. equity market. EWRS has just under 2,000 holdings and the fund allocates roughly two-thirds to micro-cap stocks, which is a corner of the equity market that is often overlooked and underrepresented in most broad-based funds. Investors who wish to minimize portfolio expenses at the cost of straying away from the equal-weight strategy can look to SCHA, which offers broad-based exposure to domestic small-caps for a minimal fee of 0.13%.:::.

Name: MSCI Singapore Index
Description: This fund tracks the MSCI Singapore Index, which reflects the performance of the Singaporean equity market. Singapore holds the number two spot as the most competitive country based on the 2011-2012 Competitiveness Report. The nation is highly regarded for its impressive infrastructure and low tax rates. Investors can access this red-hot corner of the Asian continent through EWS, which is a proxy for the performance of the Singaporean equity market. The fund holds about 30 individual components, with financial services firms receiving over two-thirds of total assets, while allocations to industrial holdings make up the next significant chunk. Exposure is further diversified across communication services, consumer goods, and real estate companies.:::.

Name: MSCI United Kingdom Index
Description: This ETF tracks the MSCI United Kingdom Index, offering investors exposure to the British equity market. Although the pound could suffer as the euro faces additional headwinds, investors who are seeking tangential exposure to this currency bloc surely value the euro free exposure provided by EWU. EWU hold a basket of 100 components and maintains a fairly balanced sector split. This ETF is comprised almost entirely of giant and large cap stocks, although minimal exposure to mid caps is also included; amongst the top holdings are HSBC, BP, Vodafone, and Royal Dutch Shell.:::.

Name: SPDR S&P Emerging Markets Small Cap

The fund is heavily weighted towards Taiwan and China, with large weightings also going towards India, South Africa, and Brazil. While many investors have a variety of choices when it comes to emerging market exposure, we believe EWX makes for a great fit because the fund is primarily invested in industrial materials and consumer goods companies, which are known to offer unparalleled growth potential, especially in environments where income and urbanization levels are rising.:::.

The index is earnings-weighted in December to reflect the proportionate share of the aggregate earnings each component company has generated. Companies with greater earnings generally have larger weights in the index

Name: Market Vectors Gold Miners ETF
Description: This ETF invests in companies engaged in mining for gold, and has significant holdings in Canada, South Africa, the U.S., Australia, the UK, and Peru. These stocks will generally exhibit a strong correlation to movements in spot gold prices. It is worth noting that although GDX’s objective is to invest in gold mining companies, some of its holdings do not derive the majority of their revenues from gold mining and instead derive their revenues from other metals such as silver. Since GDX focuses only on large and giant-cap gold mining companies, its resulting portfolio is quite shallow and heavily concentrated with only 30 individual holdings. GDX does, however, provide some exposure to emerging markets, which tend to have higher growth potentials than their developed market counterparts. The largest individual holdings of GDX are Barrick Gold Corp. (an operator of gold mines on five continents) and Newmont Mining Corp. (a diversified mining and resources company).:::.

Name: Market Vectors Junior Gold Miners ETF

As compared to larger mining companies, these “junior” companies are often more actively engaged in the development of new sources of gold through either greenfields exploration of utilizing new technologies to search for gold in abandoned ares. As such, junior gold mining companies will often be earlier stage companies, which generally have higher growth potentials. The fund’s portfolio consists of just over 70 stocks, with exposure spread across both domestic and international securities. It is important to note, however, that GDXJ does not provide a “pure play” on gold mining companies; many of its holdings are companies engaged in the extraction of other precious metals such as silver.:::.

Name: Gartman Gold/Euro ETF
Description: Invest in gold by financing gold purchases in EUR (most gold investment vehicles use the U.S. dollar for making gold purchases). Euros are obtained through the sale of either exchange-traded currency futures or “over-the-counter” foreign exchange forward contracts. PM will assess the US dollar and euro yield curve to determine the most cost effective maturity at which to borrow euros to fund gold purchases. However, the chosen maturity for funding will never exceed six months so as to minimize the exposure of the fund to longer term interest rates, which may be more volatile shorter term interest rates. Holding gold in a non-U.S. dollar denominated currency may help to limit the downside risk during stressed market environments where the U.S. dollar becomes a safe haven store of value.

Considering this fund’s targeted focus, the resulting portfolio is quite shallow with just under 30 individual holdings. Companies listed in Canada account for almost 80% of the fund’s portfolio, with the remaining assets allocated to companies from Australia, Hong Kong, and Guyana.:::.

Each share of GLTR holds a basket of gold, silver, platinum and palladium in fixed weights: 47.6% of gold, 40.3% of silver, 7.3% of platinum, and 4.8% of palladium. The gold and silver underlying the ETF are held in London, while the platinum and palladium are held in either London or Zurich.::.

This ETF may be appropriate for long-term investors looking for a unique approach to pursuing capital appreciation. It may provide an important overlay to the investor's portfolio as the advisors seek to enhance performance through emphasizing the market sectors and segments believed most promising. Different sectors within the S&P Composite 1500 typically outperform the market at various times. Market environments may cause certain sectors of businesses to perform more favorably than others. For instance, when technology companies are performing relatively well, financial companies may be taking a hit. Name: U.S. Equity High Volatility Put Write Index Fund

Investors assume the risk that the underlying referenced equities may close below their strike price, and investors also give up the upside on the underlying equities above the income the fund receives from selling the options. The strike price of each put option included in the Index must be as close as possible to 85% of the closing price of the option’s underlying stock price as of the beginning of each 60-day period.

Description: Master limited partnerships (MLPs). Given that so many MLPs are built around midstream, storage or energy transportation businesses, it’s not too surprising that the energy markets have a meaningful influence on these units. While some MLPs operate in regulated environments where prices are carefully controlled, others do not – in either case, changes in volume (often tied to the economic conditions of the region or country) can significantly impact anticipated distributions and unit prices. MLP ETFs/ETNs are best suited for those more interested in steady income accumulation as opposed to capital gains. Although MLPs don’t tend to be volatile on a day-to-day basis, they can move quite dramatically in response to new interest rate expectations or proposed changes to tax laws.

Name: Direxion S&P 500 RC Volatility Res Shrs
Interesting: S&P 500 Dynamic Rebalancing Risk Control Index
Description: The S&P 500 Dynamic Rebalancing Risk Control Index is designed to respond to the volatility of the S&P 500 Index. The S&P 500 Index measures the large capitalization segment of the domestic equity market, composed of stocks of the 500 domestic companies with the largest capitalization. The Index is composed of equity securities of the S&P 500 Index (the “Stock Component”) and fixed income securities, including U.S. Treasury Bills (the “Cash Component”). The Index responds to volatility by establishing a specific volatility target that adjusts the Index’s components among an allocation to the Stock Component and the Cash Component based upon realized exponentially-weighted historical volatility of the S&P 500 Index. The exponentially-weighted historical volatility calculation weights the more recent historical periods more heavily than older periods. As these volatility targets are met, the Index may be rebalanced as frequently as daily.

iPath S&P 500 VIX Short-term Futures ETN
Description: VXX, which is tied to the implied volatility of short-term options on t he S&P 500. Since expected volatility often rises in downward trending markets, VXX may see some nice price appreciation as the equity markets turn. Many investors have learned the hard way that correlations between many asset classes trends towards 1.0 just when it is needed most – times of economic instability. The relationship between VXX and equity markets is quite the opposite. For most of its 20-year history, the VIX Index has maintained a slight positive correlation with equity markets. But in 2008, correlation between these assets went towards negative 1.0 as equity markets plummeted and volatility surged. We think of VXX as portfolio insurance to hedge against (or in this case, profit from) a severe market downturn. CBOE Volatility Index is investable only via futures => roll-yield is important. ("rolling" is selling a near expiration futures and buying a longer-term contract)

Master limited partnerships (MLPs). Given that so many MLPs are built around midstream, storage or energy transportation businesses, it’s not too surprising that the energy markets have a meaningful influence on these units. While some MLPs operate in regulated environments where prices are carefully controlled, others do not – in either case, changes in volume (often tied to the economic conditions of the region or country) can significantly impact anticipated distributions and unit prices. MLP ETFs/ETNs are best suited for those more interested in steady income accumulation as opposed to capital gains. Although MLPs don’t tend to be volatile on a day-to-day basis, they can move quite dramatically in response to new interest rate expectations or proposed changes to tax laws.
